    "body": "This PR adds a CUDA‑aware pytest‑xdist scheduler plugin and updates the local CI script to automatically size xdist workers and support device selection.\n\nWhy\n- More predictable GPU usage when running tests in parallel. Each xdist worker gets its own visible CUDA device via `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES`, avoiding accidental cross‑GPU contention.\n- On shared hosts, we often don’t want to consume every GPU. The plugin intentionally uses only ceil(n/2) of the detected GPUs, and the script sizes total workers as `W * ceil(n/2)` with a default of `W=4` workers per selected GPU.\n- Provide a single local entry point to run tests across devices (cuda/hip/cpu/metal) with sane defaults and clear environment‑variable overrides.\n\nWhat changed\n- New plugin: `maint/scripts/pytest_cuda_scheduler.py`\n  - Discovers GPUs from `PYTEST_XDIST_CUDA_DEVICES` > `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES` > `torch.cuda.device_count()`.\n  - Keeps only `ceil(n/2)` devices from the discovered list.\n  - Allocates `W` worker slots per selected GPU (default 4; overridable via `PYTEST_XDIST_CUDA_WORKERS_PER_DEVICE`).\n  - Stamps each worker’s env with its assigned device (`CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES`) and sets an optional process title when `setproctitle` is available.\n- Local CI script: `maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh`\n  - Loads the plugin for CUDA runs and automatically computes total workers to match the plugin policy.\n  - Adds a device selector argument: `--device <cuda|hip|cpu|metal>` (default: cuda).\n  - CUDA mode: auto‑detect device list, export it when needed, compute `N = W * ceil(n/2)`, and run `pytest -p pytest_cuda_scheduler -n N`.\n  - Non‑CUDA modes (hip/cpu/metal): no device detection, no plugin; parallelism via `PYTEST_XDIST_WORKERS` (default 4).\n  - Clear usage/help comments and robust detection order (env > torch > nvidia-smi).\n\nBasic usage of run_local_ci_test.sh\n- Default CUDA run (auto workers):\n  - `bash maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh`\n- Explicit device mode:\n  - CUDA:  `bash maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh --device cuda`\n  - HIP:   `bash maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh --device hip`\n  - CPU:   `bash maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh --device cpu`\n  - Metal: `bash maint/scripts/run_local_ci_test.sh --device metal`\n- Useful env vars:\n  - `PYTHONPATH` is augmented with project root and `maint/scripts` so the plugin can be imported.\n  - `PYTEST_XDIST_CUDA_DEVICES` (e.g. `0,2,3`) to pin which GPUs are considered. If unset, the script tries `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES`, then `torch`, then `nvidia-smi`.\n  - `PYTEST_XDIST_CUDA_WORKERS_PER_DEVICE` sets `W` (default 4). Total workers in CUDA mode = `W * ceil(n/2)`.\n  - `PYTEST_XDIST_WORKERS` controls total workers for HIP/CPU/Metal (default 4).\n\nNotes\n- If no CUDA devices are found in CUDA mode, the script exits early with an error so failures are clear.\n- The plugin does not require PyTorch if the device list is provided via env vars; `torch` is only used for auto discovery.\n\n\n<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\n\n## Summary by CodeRabbit\n\n* **New Features**\n  * Introduced CUDA-aware pytest scheduler enabling GPU device allocation and per-worker pinning.\n  * Added automatic CUDA device discovery with environment-variable and library integration.\n  * Implemented environment-aware configuration for parallel test execution.\n\n* **Chores**\n  * Enhanced local CI test runner script with flexible device selection.\n  * Improved worker management with dynamic allocation based on detected devices.\n\n<sub>✏️ Tip: You can customize this high-level summary in your review settings.</sub>\n\n<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->",
